|url2=https://archive.ph/J4yrW
|text=On this day in 1977, Taiwan witnessed a watershed moment in its march to '''democracy''': the Chungli Incident. Violence broke out on the night of the largest-yet elections in the country’s history. Some 10,000 people took to the streets in protest following reports of election fraud on the part of the ruling Kuomintang.}}
# {{lb|en|countable|government}} A [[government]] under the direct or [[representative]] rule of the [[people]] of its [[jurisdiction]].
#* '''1947''', {{w|Edwin L. James}}, "General Marshall Raises the Ideological Issue", ''The New York Times'', March 16, 1947:
#*: Of course, the Russians think it is something else because they say the Russians have a '''democracy''' and it is plain that their government is not what the Americans regard as a '''democracy'''.
#* '''2003''', Fareed Zakaria, ''The Future of Freedom: Illiberal Democracy at Home and Abroad'', W. W. Norton & Company, page 13:
#*: In 1900 not a single country had what we would today consider a '''democracy''': a government created by elections in which every adult citizen could vote.
# {{lb|en|countable}} A [[state]] with a [[democratic]] system of [[government]].
#* '''2018''', Yascha Mounk, “America Is Not a Democracy”, ''The Atlantic'', March 2018:
